XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY:
This five-vehicle crash occurred on a two lane undivided roadway. The roadway consisted of one through lane for the north and southbound directions with each lane bordered by paved asphalt shoulders. The roadway was straight, downhill, and bituminous with a posted speed limit of 48 kmph (30 mph) in the southbound direction. The crash occurred during nighttime hours with no traffic congestion. The roadway was extremely icy at the time of the crash and covered with a combination of snow , ice and slush.
Vehicle one (V1), a 2003 Chrysler PT Cruiser with two occupants present was southbound in lane one. Vehicle two (V2), a Pontiac Grand Prix with two occupants was southbound in lane one behind V1. Vehicle three (V3), a 1990 Honda Accord with two occupants was also southbound in lane one behind V2. Vehicle four (V4), a 1994 Dodge Dakota with only the driver present was southbound in lane one behind V3. And vehicle five (V5), a Mazda 6 with only the driver present was southbound in lane one behind V4. V1 started to lose control due to the icy roads and started to rotate clockwise approximately 90 degrees. The driver of V2 saw that V1 was losing control and attempted to slow down. V2 was unable to slow down and also started to rotate clockwise. V1 contacted the left side of V2 with its right side. The driver of V3 which was behind V1 and V2 saw all of this and attempted to avoid the collision but had no place to go and ended up contacting V2's right side with it's left front corner. V4, going southbound, then contacted the back right corner of V3 with its front. This caused vehicle three to rotate clockwise and V4 to rotate counter clockwise and side slap. V3 and V4 rotated 180 degrees opposite of each other and parallel to southbound traffic before V4 was contacted by V5's front end to V4's left side. V1 came to rest partially in a private driveway facing southwest on all four tires. V2 came to rest on all four tires in lane one facing southwest. V3 came to rest in lane one facing west on all four tires, but was moved prior to the researcher's arrival on-scene. V4 came to rest on all four tires facing east in lane one. V5 came to rest in lane one on all four tires facing southeast. V1, V2, V4 and V5 were towed due to damage.
Little is known about the driver of V1, a 42 year old female, due to a lack of driver interview.
The driver of V2, a 17-year-old male, was on his way home from picking up a friend when the crash occurred. He stated being rested, drives this route daily and is very comfortable with this vehicle. He also stated being in good health and takes no medications.
The driver of V3, a 39-year-old female, was on her way home from shopping when the crash occurred. She stated being rested, drives this route weekly and is very comfortable with this vehicle. She stated being in good health and takes no medications. Prior to the collision she and the passenger were having a social conversation, and she was worried about the poor road conditions.
The critical pre-crash event for V1 was coded: this vehicle control loss due to, poor road conditions (specified as: icy roadway). The critical reason for the critical event was not coded to this vehicle.
The critical pre-crash event for V2 was coded: other motor vehicle in lane; traveling in same direction while decelerating. The critical reason for the critical pre-crash event for V1 was coded as an environmental related factor: slick roads (low friction road surface due to ice, loose debris, any other cause).
V3, V4 and V5 were not involved in the first harmful event. The critical reason for the critical pre-crash event was not coded to these vehicles.
